# Clean Rebuilds

When replacing or redesigning an existing subsystem, remove the superseded code instead of keeping the old path around "just in case".

- Do not keep legacy fallbacks unless the user explicitly asks for backward compatibility.
- Do not leave dead UI paths, unused helpers, duplicate controllers, or obsolete event wiring after a rebuild.
- If a new implementation replaces an old one, update all callers to the new path and delete the old path in the same task when safe.
- Prefer a temporary stub only when needed to avoid breaking unrelated code during an in-progress refactor. Remove it before finishing.
- Before ending the task, search for lingering references to the replaced code and clean them up.

Examples:

```text
Bad: add NewFileSystem(), but keep OldFileBrowser.showModal(), old save dialogs, and old script includes.
Good: switch all callers to NewFileSystem(), remove old browser/dialog code, and delete obsolete files/includes.
```
